<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
<A STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:9PT;" HREF="#MA12312016-10XK_HTM_SCE310DA1AD275D4581A5EF6AA8B08CA8">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	MASTERCARD INCORPORATED
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:6PX;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS &#8211; (Continued)
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Settlement due from/due to customers
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company operates systems for clearing and settling payment transactions among Mastercard customers. Net settlements are generally cleared daily among customers through settlement cash accounts by wire transfer or other bank clearing means. However, some transactions may not settle until subsequent business days, resulting in amounts due from and due to Mastercard customers.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Restricted security deposits held for Mastercard customers
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- Mastercard requires collateral from certain customers for settlement of their transactions. The majority of collateral for settlement is in the form of standby letters of credit and bank guarantees which are not recorded on the consolidated balance sheet. Additionally, Mastercard holds cash deposits and certificates of deposit from certain customers of Mastercard as collateral for settlement of their transactions, which are recorded as assets on the consolidated balance sheet. These assets are fully offset by corresponding liabilities included on the consolidated balance sheet.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Property, plant and equipment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- Property, plant and equipment are stated at cost less accumulated depreciation and amortization. Depreciation and amortization is computed using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets. Depreciation of leasehold improvements and amortization of capital leases is included in depreciation and amortization expense.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The useful lives of the Company&#8217;s assets are as follows:
</FONT>
</DIV>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_37"></A>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<DIV STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PX;TEXT-INDENT:0PX;LINE-HEIGHT:NORMAL;PADDING-TOP:10PX;">
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;MARGIN-LEFT:AUTO;MARGIN-RIGHT:AUTO;WIDTH:537PX;BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;">

</TD>

</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:266PX;">
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

	Asset Category
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">

	&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;BACKGROUND-COLOR:;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

	Estimated Useful Life
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Buildings
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">

	&#160;

</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;BORDER-TOP:1PX SOLID #000000;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	30 years
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Building equipment
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="OVERFLOW:HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#160;

</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	10 - 15 years
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Furniture and fixtures and equipment
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="OVERFLOW:HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2 - 5 years
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Leasehold improvements
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="OVERFLOW:HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Shorter of life of improvement or lease term
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Capital leases
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="OVERFLOW:HIDDEN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:MIDDLE;BACKGROUND-COLOR:#CCEEFF;PADDING-LEFT:2PX;PADDING-TOP:2PX;PADDING-BOTTOM:2PX;PADDING-RIGHT:2PX;">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Shorter of life of the asset or lease term
</FONT>
</DIV>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Leases
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company enters into operating and capital leases for the use of premises and equipment. Rent expense related to lease agreements that contain lease incentives is recorded on a straight-line basis over the term of the lease.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Pension and other postretirement plans
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company recognizes the funded status of its single-employer defined benefit pension plans or postretirement plans as assets or liabilities on its consolidated balance sheet and recognizes changes in the funded status in the year in which the changes occur through accumulated other comprehensive income (loss). The funded status is measured as the difference between the fair value of plan assets and the benefit obligation at December 31, the measurement date. The fair value of plan assets represents the current market value of the pension assets. Overfunded plans are aggregated and recorded in long-term other assets, while underfunded plans are aggregated and recorded as accrued expenses and long-term other liabilities.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Net periodic pension and postretirement benefit cost/(income) is recognized in general and administrative expenses in the consolidated statement of operations. These costs include service costs, interest cost, expected return on plan assets, amortization of prior service costs or credits and gains or losses previously recognized as a component of accumulated other comprehensive income (loss).
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Defined contribution plans
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company&#8217;s contributions to defined contribution plans are recorded when employees render service to the Company. The charge is recorded in general and administrative expenses in the consolidated statement of operations.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Advertising and marketing
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The cost of media advertising is expensed when the advertising takes place. Advertising production costs are expensed as incurred. Promotional items are expensed at the time the promotional event occurs. Sponsorship costs are recognized over the period of benefit.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Foreign currency remeasurement and translation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- Monetary assets and liabilities are remeasured to functional currencies using current exchange rates in effect at the balance sheet date. Non-monetary assets and liabilities are recorded at historical exchange rates. Revenue and expense accounts are remeasured at the weighted-average exchange rate for the period. Resulting exchange gains and losses related to remeasurement are included in general and administrative expenses on the consolidated statement of operations.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Where a non-U.S. currency is the functional currency, translation from that functional currency to U.S. dollars is performed for balance sheet accounts using current exchange rates in effect at the balance sheet date and for revenue and expense accounts
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	64
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
<A NAME="eolPage65"></A>
<DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
<A STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:9PT;" HREF="#MA12312016-10XK_HTM_SCE310DA1AD275D4581A5EF6AA8B08CA8">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	MASTERCARD INCORPORATED
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:6PX;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS &#8211; (Continued)
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	using a weighted-average exchange rate for the period. Resulting translation adjustments are reported as a component of accumulated other comprehensive income (loss).
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Treasury stock
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company records the repurchase of shares of its common stock at cost on the trade date of the transaction. These shares are considered treasury stock, which is a reduction to stockholders&#8217; equity. Treasury stock is included in authorized and issued shares but excluded from outstanding shares.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Share-based payments
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company measures share-based compensation expense at the grant date, based on the estimated fair value of the award and uses the straight-line method of attribution, net of estimated forfeitures, for expensing awards over the requisite employee service period. The Company estimates the fair value of its non-qualified stock option awards (&#8220;Options&#8221;) using a Black-Scholes valuation model. The fair value of restricted stock units (&#8220;RSUs&#8221;) is determined and fixed on the grant date based on the Company&#8217;s stock price, adjusted for the exclusion of dividend equivalents. The Monte Carlo simulation valuation model is used to determine the grant date fair value of performance stock units (&#8220;PSUs&#8221;) granted. All share-based compensation expenses are recorded in general and administrative expenses.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Earnings per share
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	- The Company calculates basic earnings per share (&#8220;EPS&#8221;) by dividing net income by the weighted-average number of common shares outstanding during the year. Diluted EPS is calculated by dividing net income by the weighted-average number of common shares outstanding during the year, adjusted for the potentially dilutive effect of stock options and unvested stock units using the treasury stock method.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Recent accounting pronouncements
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Goodwill impairment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In January 2017, the FASB issued accounting guidance to simplify how companies are required to test goodwill for impairment. Under this new guidance, step 2 of the goodwill impairment test has been eliminated. Step 2 of the goodwill impairment test required companies to determine the implied fair value of the reporting unit&#8217;s goodwill. Under this new guidance, companies will perform their annual, or interim, goodwill impairment test by comparing the reporting unit&#8217;s carrying value, including goodwill, to the fair value. An impairment charge would be recorded if the carrying value exceeds the reporting unit&#8217;s fair value. The guidance is required to be applied prospectively and is effective for periods beginning after December 15, 2020, with early adoption permitted. The Company expects to early adopt this accounting guidance effective January 1, 2017. The Company does not expect any impact from the adoption of the new accounting guidance on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Restricted cash
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In December 2016, the FASB issued accounting guidance to address diversity in the classification and presentation of changes in restricted cash on the statement of cash flows. Under this guidance, companies will be required to present restricted cash and restricted cash equivalents with cash and cash equivalents when reconciling the beginning-of-period and end-of-period amounts shown on the statement of cash flows. The guidance is required to be applied retrospectively and is effective for periods beginning after December 15, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company expects to adopt this accounting guidance effective January 1, 2018. Upon adoption of this standard, the Company will include restricted cash, which currently consists of restricted cash for litigation settlement and restricted security deposits held for customers in its reconciliation of beginning-of-period and end-of-period cash and cash equivalents on the statement of cash flows.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Intra-entity asset transfers
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In October 2016, the FASB issued accounting guidance to simplify the accounting for income tax consequences of intra-entity transfers of assets other than inventory. Under this guidance, companies will be required to recognize the income tax consequences of an intra-entity asset transfer when the transfer occurs. The guidance must be applied on a modified retrospective basis through a cumulative-effect adjustment to retained earnings as of the period of adoption. The guidance is effective for periods beginning after December 15, 2017 and early adoption is permitted. The Company expects to adopt this accounting guidance effective January 1, 2018. The Company is in the process of evaluating the impacts this guidance will have on its consolidated financial statements. However, the Company expects that it will recognize a cumulative-effect adjustment to retained earnings upon adoption of the new guidance related to any deferred income tax consequence from intra-entity asset transfers occurring before the date of adoption. See Note 17 (Income Taxes) for additional information related to intra-entity asset transfers that will be impacted by this guidance.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Share-based payments
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In March 2016, the FASB
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#32;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	issued accounting guidance related to share-based payments to employees. Under this guidance, companies will be required to recognize the tax effects of exercised or vested awards within the income statement, in the period in which they occur, rather than within additional paid-in-capital. In addition, the guidance changes the limit that companies are allowed to withhold for employees without triggering liability accounting and allows companies to make a policy election to either recognize forfeitures as they occur or estimate them. The guidance is effective for periods beginning after December 15, 2016 and early adoption is permitted. The required transition methods for each aspect of the guidance vary
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	65
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>

<A NAME="eolPage66"></A>
<DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
<A STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:9PT;" HREF="#MA12312016-10XK_HTM_SCE310DA1AD275D4581A5EF6AA8B08CA8">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	MASTERCARD INCORPORATED
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:6PX;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS &#8211; (Continued)
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	between prospective, retrospective and modified retrospective. The Company will adopt the accounting guidance effective January 1, 2017 and the impact on the tax provision during the period will be dependent upon several factors including, the amount and grant value of equity awards that either vest or are exercised, in addition to, Mastercard&#8217;s share price on those dates. The requirement to recognize the tax effects of exercised or vested awards in the income statement, rather than within additional paid-in-capital, will be adopted prospectively. If this aspect of the new guidance had been in effect for each of the periods presented, the Company&#8217;s tax provision in 2016, 2015 and 2014 would have been adjusted for a tax benefit of $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	48 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	42 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	54 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively, in its income statement. The Company is in the process of evaluating the other potential effects this guidance will have on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Leases
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In February 2016, the FASB issued accounting guidance that will change how companies account for and present lease arrangements. The guidance requires companies to recognize leased assets and liabilities for both capital and operating leases. The guidance is effective for periods after December 15, 2018 and early adoption is permitted. Companies are required to adopt the guidance using a modified retrospective method. The Company is in the process of evaluating the potential effects this guidance will have on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Debt issuance costs
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In April 2015, the FASB issued accounting guidance that changed the current presentation of debt issuance costs on the consolidated balance sheet. This guidance moved debt issuance costs from the assets section of the consolidated balance sheet to the liabilities section as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of the debt issued. The Company adopted the accounting guidance effective January 1, 2016. The Company applied the guidance retrospectively and, as such, the December&#160;31, 2015 consolidated balance sheet was adjusted to reflect the effects of the standard. This retrospective adjustment resulted in reductions of prepaid expenses and other current assets, other assets and long-term debt by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$18 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$19 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively. As of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$33 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of debt issuance costs were classified as an offset to long-term debt.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Revenue recognition
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;- In May 2014, the FASB issued accounting guidance that provides a single, comprehensive revenue recognition model for all contracts with customers and supersedes most of the existing revenue recognition requirements. Under this guidance, an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. In August 2015, the FASB issued accounting guidance that delayed the effective date of this standard by one year, making the guidance effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2017. The new revenue guidance will impact the timing of recognition for certain of the Company&#8217;s customer incentives. Under the new guidance, the Company will recognize certain customer incentives over the life of the contract as revenue is recognized versus as they are earned by the customer. The Company will adopt the new accounting guidance effective January 1, 2018. The accounting guidance permits either a full retrospective or a modified retrospective transition method. The Company expects to adopt the new guidance with the modified retrospective transition method. The Company is in the process of quantifying the potential effects this guidance will have on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<A NAME="MA12312016-10XK_HTM_SC6518495086057AB95F89774300EC5BB">
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 2.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Acquisitions
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On July 21, 2016, Mastercard entered into a definitive agreement to acquire a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	92.4%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;controlling interest in VocaLink Holdings Limited (&#8220;VocaLink&#8221;) for approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#163;700 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;(approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$860 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	) after adjusting for cash and certain other estimated liabilities. VocaLink&#8217;s existing shareholders have the potential for an earn-out of up to an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#163;169 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;(approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$210 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	) if certain performance targets are met.&#160; Under the agreement, a majority of VocaLink&#8217;s shareholders will retain
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	7.6%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;ownership for at least
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	three years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.&#160; VocaLink operates payments clearing systems and ATM switching platforms in the U.K., as well as several other regions.&#160; While the Company anticipates completing the transaction by the middle of 2017, it is subject to regulatory approval and other customary closing conditions.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the Company acquired
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;businesses for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$609 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in cash. For these acquisitions, the Company recorded
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$481 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as goodwill representing the aggregate excess of the purchase consideration over the fair value of the net assets acquired. In 2014, the Company acquired
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	eight
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;businesses,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of which were achieved in stages, with non-controlling interests acquired in previous years.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	One
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of the business combinations was a transaction for less than 100 percent of the equity interest. The total consideration transferred was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$575 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, of which
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$509 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;was recorded as goodwill.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	A portion of the goodwill related to the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and 2014 acquisitions is expected to be deductible for local tax purposes. The consolidated financial statements include the operating results of the acquired businesses from the dates of their respective acquisition. Pro forma information related to the acquisitions was not included because the impact on the Company&#8217;s consolidated results of operations was not considered to be material.
</FONT>
</DIV>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Fair Value and Investment Securities
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Financial Instruments - Recurring Measurements
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company classifies its fair value measurements of financial instruments into a three-level hierarchy (the &#8220;Valuation Hierarchy&#8221;). There were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;transfers made among the three levels in the Valuation Hierarchy for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;PADDING-LEFT:48PX;TEXT-INDENT:-6PX;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<SUP STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:PT">
	1
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	Excludes amounts held in escrow related to the U.S. merchant class litigation settlement of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	$543 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	$541 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	, respectively, which would be included in Level 1 of the Valuation Hierarchy. See
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	Note 10 (Accrued Expenses and Accrued Litigation)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	Note 18 (Legal and Regulatory Proceedings)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;for further details.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The fair value of the Company&#8217;s available-for-sale municipal securities, government and agency securities, corporate securities and asset-backed securities are based on quoted prices for similar assets in active markets and are therefore included in Level 2 of the Valuation Hierarchy. The Company&#8217;s foreign currency derivative asset and liability contracts have also been classified within Level 2 in the Other category of the Valuation Hierarchy, as the fair value is based on broker quotes for the same or similar derivative instruments. See
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Note 20 (Foreign Exchange Risk Management)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;for further details. The Company&#8217;s U.S. government securities and marketable equity securities are classified within Level 1 of the Valuation Hierarchy as the fair values are based on unadjusted quoted prices for identical assets in active markets.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Financial Instruments - Non-Recurring Measurements
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Certain financial instruments are carried on the consolidated balance sheet at cost, which approximates fair value due to their short-term, highly liquid nature. These instruments include cash and cash equivalents, restricted cash, time deposits, accounts receivable, settlement due from customers, restricted security deposits held for customers, accounts payable, settlement due to customers and accrued expenses. In addition, nonmarketable equity investments are measured at fair value on a nonrecurring basis for purposes of initial recognition and impairment testing.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:12PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Investments on the consolidated balance sheet include both available-for-sale and short-term held-to-maturity securities. Available-for-sale securities are measured at fair value on a recurring basis and are included in the Valuation Hierarchy table above. Short-term held-to-maturity securities are made up of time deposits with maturities of greater than three months and less than one year and are classified as Level 2 of the Valuation Hierarchy, but are not included in the table above due to their fair values not being measured on a recurring basis. At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the cost, which approximates fair value, of the Company&#8217;s short-term held-to-maturity securities was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$452 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$130 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively. In addition, at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the Company held
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$61 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of long-term held-to-maturity securities included in other assets on the consolidated balance sheet, the cost of which approximates fair value, which are classified as Level 2 of the Valuation Hierarchy.
</FONT>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	MASTERCARD INCORPORATED
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:6PX;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS &#8211; (Continued)
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:12PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Debt
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:12PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company estimates the fair value of its long-term debt based on market quotes for the debt instruments. Long-term debt is classified as Level 2 of the Valuation Hierarchy. At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the carrying value and fair value of long-term debt was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$5.2 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$5.3 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively. At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the carrying value and fair value of long-term debt was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.3 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Settlement and Other Guarantee Liabilities
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company estimates the fair value of its settlement and other guarantees using market assumptions for relevant though not directly comparable undertakings, as the latter are not observable in the market given the proprietary nature of such guarantees. At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December 31, 2016 and 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the carrying value and fair value of settlement and other guarantee liabilities were not material. Settlement and other guarantee liabilities are classified as Level 3 of the Valuation Hierarchy as their valuation requires substantial judgment and estimation of factors that are not currently observable in the market. For additional information regarding the Company&#8217;s settlement and other guarantee liabilities, see
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Note 19 (Settlement and Other Risk Management)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Non-Financial Instruments
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Certain assets are measured at fair value on a nonrecurring basis for purposes of initial recognition and impairment testing. The Company&#8217;s non-financial assets measured at fair value on a nonrecurring basis include property, plant and equipment, goodwill and other intangible assets. These assets are subject to fair value adjustments in certain circumstances, such as when there is evidence of impairment.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Amortized Costs and Fair Values &#8211; Available-for-Sale Investment Securities
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The major classes of the Company&#8217;s available-for-sale investment securities, for which unrealized gains and losses are recorded as a separate component of other comprehensive income on the consolidated statement of comprehensive income, and their respective amortized cost basis and fair values as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December 31, 2016 and 2015

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Customer and merchant incentives represent payments made or amounts to be paid to customers and merchants under business agreements. Costs directly related to entering into such an agreement are generally deferred and amortized over the life of the agreement. Amounts to be paid for these incentives and the related liability were included in accrued expenses and other liabilities.
</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Non-current prepaid income taxes, included in the other asset table above, primarily consists of taxes paid in the fourth quarter of 2014 relating to the deferred charge resulting from the reorganization of our legal entity and tax structure to better align with our business footprint of our non-U.S. operations.
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	denominated in foreign currencies. As such, the change in intangible assets includes a component attributable to foreign currency translation. Based on the qualitative assessment performed in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, it was determined that the Company&#8217;s indefinite-lived intangible assets were not impaired.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016, 2015 and 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively. The following table sets forth the estimated future amortization expense on amortizable intangible assets on the consolidated balance sheet at

	2015

	, the Company&#8217;s provision for litigation was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$722 million

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$709 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively. These amounts are not included in the accrued expenses table above and are separately reported as accrued litigation on the consolidated balance sheet. See
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Note 18 (Legal and Regulatory Proceedings)

	&#32;for further discussion of the U.S. merchant class litigation.

<DIV>
<A NAME="MA12312016-10XK_HTM_SBFD87CF2C1555D4B898C64A0588B2293">
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 11.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Pension, Postretirement and Savings Plans
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Defined Contribution
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company sponsors defined contribution retirement plans. The primary plan is the Mastercard Savings Plan, a 401(k) plan for substantially all of the U.S. employees, which is subject to the provisions of the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (&#8220;ERISA&#8221;), as amended. In addition, the Company has several defined contribution plans outside of the U.S. The Company&#8217;s total expense for its defined contribution plans was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$73 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$61 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$57 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2016, 2015 and 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Defined Benefit and Other Postretirement Plans
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	During the third quarter of 2015, the Company terminated its non-contributory, qualified, U.S. defined benefit pension plan (the &#8220;U.S. Employee Pension Plan&#8221;). The U.S. Employee Pension Plan participants had the option to receive a lump sum distribution or to participate in an annuity with a third-party insurance company. As a result of this termination, the Company settled its obligation for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$287 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, which resulted in a pension settlement charge of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$79 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;recorded in general and administrative expense during 2015.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company maintains a postretirement plan providing health coverage and life insurance benefits for substantially all of its U.S. employees hired before July 1, 2007 (&#8220;U.S. Postretirement Plan&#8221;). The U.S. postretirement plan was unfunded and the Company&#8217;s obligation was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$59 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, and was recorded in Other Liabilities. The Company&#8217;s total expense for its U.S. postretirement plan was not material to the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	72
</FONT>
</DIV>

	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	MASTERCARD INCORPORATED
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:6PX;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTES TO CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS &#8211; (Continued)
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<BR>
</FONT>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company sponsors pension and postretirement plans for non-U.S. employees (&#8220;non-U.S. plans&#8221;) that cover various benefits specific to their country of employment. The Company recognizes the funded status of its defined benefit pension plans and other postretirement benefit plans, measured as the difference between the fair value of the plan assets and the projected benefit obligation, in the Consolidated Balance Sheet. The non-U.S. plans do not have a material impact on the Company&#8217;s consolidated financial statements, individually or in the aggregate.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<A NAME="MA12312016-10XK_HTM_S16F4EBF11D055018807B287C82D98A47">
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 12.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#32;Debt
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In November 2016, the Company issued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$2 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;aggregate principal amount of notes (the &#8220;2016 USD Notes&#8221;). Interest on the 2016 USD Notes is payable semi-annually.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In December&#160;2015, the Company issued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#8364;1.65 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;(
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.74 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;as translated at the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;exchange rate) aggregate principal amount of notes (the &#8220;2015 Euro Notes&#8221;). Interest on the 2015 Euro Notes is payable annually.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In March 2014, the Company issued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.5 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;aggregate principal amount of notes (the &#8220;2014 USD Notes&#8221;). Interest on the 2014 USD Notes is payable semi-annually.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The net proceeds, after deducting the original issue discount, underwriting discount and offering expenses, from the issuance of the 2016 USD Notes, the 2015 Euro Notes and the 2014 USD Notes, were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.969 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.723 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$1.484 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, respectively.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company is not subject to any financial covenants under the 2016 USD Notes, the 2015 Euro Notes and the 2014 USD Notes (collectively the &#8220;Notes&#8221;). The Notes may be redeemed in whole, or in part, at our option at any time for a specified make-whole amount. The Notes are senior unsecured obligations and would rank equally with any future unsecured and unsubordinated indebtedness. The proceeds of the Notes are to be used for general corporate purposes.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Long-term debt consisted of the following at December 31:

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In November 2015, the Company established a commercial paper program (the &#8220;Commercial Paper Program&#8221;). Under the Commercial Paper Program, the Company is authorized to issue up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.75 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;in outstanding notes, with maturities up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	397
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;days from the date of issuance. The Commercial Paper Program is available in U.S. dollars.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In conjunction with the Commercial Paper Program, the Company entered into a committed unsecured
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.75 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;revolving credit facility (the &#8220;Credit Facility&#8221;) in October 2015. The Credit Facility amended and restated the Company&#8217;s prior credit facility. Borrowings under the Credit Facility are available in U.S. dollars and/or euros. In October 2016, the Company extended the Credit Facility for an additional year to October 2021. The extension did not result in any material changes to the terms and conditions of the Credit Facility. The facility fee and borrowing cost under the Credit Facility are based upon the Company&#8217;s credit rating. At
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	, the applicable facility fee was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;basis points on the average daily commitment (whether or not utilized). In addition to the facility fee, interest on borrowings under the Credit Facility would be charged at the London Interbank Offered Rate (LIBOR) plus an applicable margin of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	79.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;basis points, or an alternative base rate. The Credit Facility contains customary representations, warranties, events of default and affirmative and negative covenants, including a financial covenant limiting the maximum level of consolidated debt to earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization (EBITDA). Mastercard was in compliance in all material respects with the covenants of the Credit Facility at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The majority of Credit Facility lenders are customers or affiliates of customers of Mastercard.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Borrowings under the Commercial Paper Program and the Credit Facility are used to provide liquidity for general corporate purposes, including providing liquidity in the event of one or more settlement failures by the Company&#8217;s customers. The Company may borrow and repay amounts under the Commercial Paper Program and Credit Facility from time to time. Mastercard had no borrowings under the Credit Facility and the Commercial Paper Program at
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	December&#160;31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On June 15, 2015, the Company filed a universal shelf registration statement to provide additional access to capital, if needed. Pursuant to the shelf registration statement, the Company may from time to time offer to sell debt securities, preferred stock, Class A common stock, depository shares, purchase contracts, units or warrants in one or more offerings.
</FONT>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Class B Common Stock Conversions
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Shares of Class B common stock are convertible on a one-for-one basis into shares of Class A common stock.&#160; Entities eligible to hold Mastercard&#8217;s Class B common stock are defined in the Company&#8217;s amended and restated certificate of incorporation (generally the Company&#8217;s principal or affiliate customers), and they are restricted from retaining ownership of shares of Class A common stock.&#160; Class B stockholders are required to subsequently sell or otherwise transfer any shares of Class A common stock received pursuant to such a conversion.&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	The MasterCard Foundation
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In connection and simultaneously with its 2006 initial public offering (the &#8220;IPO&#8221;), the Company issued and donated
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	135 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;newly authorized shares of Class A common stock to The MasterCard Foundation (the &#8220;Foundation&#8221;). The Foundation is a private charitable foundation incorporated in Canada that is controlled by directors who are independent of the Company and its principal customers. Under the terms of the donation, the Foundation became able to resell the donated shares in May 2010 and to the extent necessary to meet charitable disbursement requirements dictated by Canadian tax law. Under Canadian tax law, the Foundation is generally required to disburse at least
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	3.5%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of its assets not used in administration each year for qualified charitable disbursements. However, the Foundation obtained permission from the Canadian tax authorities to defer the giving requirements for up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	ten
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;years, which was extended in 2011 to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	fifteen
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;years. The Foundation, at its discretion, may decide to meet its disbursement obligations on an annual basis or to settle previously accumulated obligations during any given year. The Foundation will be permitted to sell all of its remaining shares beginning twenty years and eleven months after the consummation of the IPO.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Stock Repurchase Programs
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On February 5, 2013, the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors approved a share repurchase program authorizing the Company to repurchase up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	$2 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of its Class A common stock (the &#8220;February 2013 Share Repurchase Program&#8221;), which became effective in March 2013.&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On December 10, 2013, the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors approved a share repurchase program authorizing the Company to repurchase up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.5 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of its Class A common stock (the &#8220;December 2013 Share Repurchase Program&#8221;), which became effective in January 2014.&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On December 2, 2014, the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors approved a share repurchase program authorizing the Company to repurchase up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$3.75 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of its Class A common stock (the &#8220;December 2014 Share Repurchase Program&#8221;), which became effective in January 2015.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On December 8, 2015, the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors approved a share repurchase program authorizing the Company to repurchase up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$4 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of its Class A common stock (the &#8220;December 2015 Share Repurchase Program&#8221;), which became effective in February 2016.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	On December 6, 2016, the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors approved a share repurchase program authorizing the Company to repurchase up to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	$4 billion
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;of its Class A common stock (the &#8220;December 2016 Share Repurchase Program&#8221;). The December 2016 Share Repurchase Program will become effective after completion of the December 2015 Share Repurchase Program.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	75

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;PADDING-LEFT:48PX;TEXT-INDENT:-6PX;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<SUP STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:PT">
	1
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	During 2015, the increase in other comprehensive loss related to foreign currency translation adjustments was driven primarily by the devaluation of the euro and Brazilian real. During 2016, the increase in other comprehensive loss related to foreign currency translation adjustments was driven primarily by the devaluation of the British pound and euro.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;PADDING-LEFT:48PX;TEXT-INDENT:-6PX;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<SUP STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:PT">
	2
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	During 2015,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	$80 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;of deferred costs (
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	$51 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;after-tax) related to the Company&#8217;s defined benefit pension plan and other post retirement plans were reclassified to general and administrative expenses. The deferred costs were driven primarily by the termination of the Company's U.S. defined benefit plan (See
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	Note 11 (Pension, Postretirement and Savings Plans)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	). During 2016, deferred gains related to the Company&#8217;s postretirement plans, reclassified from accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) to earnings, were $
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	1 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;before and after tax.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:8PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;PADDING-LEFT:48PX;TEXT-INDENT:-6PX;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
<SUP STYLE="VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP;LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:PT">
	3
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	During 2015,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	$15 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	&#32;of an unrealized loss (no tax impact) on a foreign denominated available-for-sale security was reclassified to other income (expense) due to an other-than-temporary impairment. During 2016, gains and losses on available-for-sale investment securities, reclassified from accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) to investment income, were not significant.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<A NAME="MA12312016-10XK_HTM_SD14F6A883B265386A4C5D9C205C896A6">
</A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 15.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Share-Based Payments
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	In May 2006, the Company implemented the Mastercard Incorporated 2006 Long-Term Incentive Plan, which was amended and restated as of June 5, 2012 (the &#8220;LTIP&#8221;). The LTIP is a stockholder-approved plan that permits the grant of various types of equity awards to employees.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	The Company has granted Options, RSUs and PSUs under the LTIP. The Options, which expire
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	ten years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;from the date of grant, generally vest ratably over
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	four years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;from the date of grant. The RSUs and PSUs generally vest after
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-DECORATION:NONE;">
	three years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	. The Company uses the straight-line method of attribution for expensing equity awards. Compensation expense is recorded net of estimated forfeitures. Estimates are adjusted as appropriate.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Upon termination of employment, a participant&#8217;s unvested awards are forfeited. However, when a participant terminates employment due to disability or retirement more than
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	six months
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;after receiving the award, the participant retains all of their awards without providing additional service to the Company. Retirement eligibility is dependent upon age and years of service. Compensation expense is recognized over the shorter of the vesting periods stated in the LTIP or the date the individual becomes eligible to retire but not less than
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	six months
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;PADDING-TOP:13PX;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	There are approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	116 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&#32;shares of Class A common stock authorized for equity awards under the LTIP. Although the LTIP permits the issuance of shares of Class B common stock, no such shares have been authorized for issuance. Shares issued as a result of Option exercises and the conversions of RSUs and PSUs were funded primarily with the issuance of new shares of Class A common stock.
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:120%;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:CALIBRI,SANS-SERIF;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	77
</FONT>

	The fair value of each RSU is the closing stock price on the New York Stock Exchange of the Company&#8217;s Class A common stock on the date of grant, adjusted for the exclusion of dividend equivalents. Upon vesting, a portion of the RSU award may be withheld to satisfy the minimum statutory withholding taxes. The remaining RSUs will be settled in shares of the Company&#8217;s Class A
